  "prompt": "What is Tacometer?",
  "response": "A tachometer (often misspelled as \"tacometer\") is an instrument used to measure the rotational speed of an object, typically a shaft or a disk. It is usually expressed in revolutions per minute (RPM). Tachometers are commonly found in various applications, including:\n\n1. **Automobiles**: In vehicles, tachometers display engine speed, helping drivers understand how hard the engine is working, which can be vital for performance and fuel efficiency.\n2. **Industrial Equipment**: Used in machinery to monitor the speed of motors and other rotating components to ensure proper operation and to prevent mechanical failures.\n3. **Aircraft**: Tachometers in aircraft measure the rotational speed of propellers or turbines, which is crucial for safe flight operations.\n\nTachometers can be analog or digital. Analog tachometers typically use a dial and needle to indicate speed, while digital tachometers display readings in a numerical format. Some advanced systems may also include features such as data logging, peak hold functions, or integration with other monitoring systems.",
